            "answer_text": "The term khan is entirely unrelated to religion. The Mongols first used it when it was assigned to Tem\u00fcjin (later Genghis Khan) after he successfully united the Mongolian tribes in 1206 CE. However, the term had been used by many other civilizations before this to denote a \u201cchief\u201d or \u201cruler.\u201d Its origins have nothing to do with Islam - it was used to refer to a chief or emperor by nomadic civilizations long before Muhammad created the religion. It wasn\u2019t even an originally Arabic term. Long after Genghis Khan, however, the term was connected to Islam when it was used by the Muslim rulers of the Russian khanate of the Golden Horde.  Tode Mongke, a Muslim leader of the Golden Horde, leading his troops on horseback Thus, although he was Tengrist, and not Muslim, Genghis Khan, meaning \u201cuniversal ruler,\u201d received the title of Khan because it had little to do with religion: it was simply a title of power and rank. Khan was used to refer to Mongol rulers of varying religion many years after Genghis Khan\u2019s death in 1227 CE.  Genghis Khan ",
