            },
            "answer_text": "\u201cKhan\u201d is not an exclusively or even originally Muslim name or office. It\u2019s Mongolian and made its way into other languages during the later Middle Ages. It\u2019s a bit like how \u201ctsar,\u201d a derivative of \u201cCaesar,\u201d could be used by Orthodox Christian, Slavic speaking Russian rulers who were in no way pagan Italians. Khan and variants on it like khagan originate from Turkic and Mongolian languages spoken on the steppes of Central Asia. They mostly stayed there until the Mongol empire of the 13th century rolled over most of Asia. When the empire broke up a generation later, most regions of the empire retained a Mongol ruling family and at least partly Mongolized ruling class, but some of them moved culturally and religiously closer to the people they ruled. Notably, some (for example, in the Ilkhanate of southwestern Asia) converted to Islam. In this way, the word \u201ckhan\u201d entered Persian, Arabic, and other languages in or adjacent to what had been the Mongol empire. ",
